Add the TOY (time of year) class to timetools.

At the moment, this TOY is supposed to support the "SeasonalParameter" class (will be implemented later).  TOY instances help to define time points in each year, that are used as node points for the definition of seasonal patterns.

Allow TOY objects as initialization arguments for class Date.

Note that the year is generally set to 2000, which is a leap year.

Add some methods to the TOY class.

 - Comparison methods, e.g. __eq__

 - __sub__

 - passed_seconds and left_seconds

 - __dir__

Introduce the SeasonalParameter class.

This class is supposed to define seasonal patterns and relies on TOY (time of year) objects. So far, only the methods __init__, __call__, and _setshape have been implemented.

Small improvements on parametertools

 - TOY is now hashable

 - some PEP8 related fixes

Some improvements on SeasonalParameter

Note that SeasonalParameter still does not work properly.

 - make the toy2values dictionary private

 - add the methods __iter__, __repr__, __len__ and __dir__ (should be ok, but are not tested yet

 - add the methods __getattr__, __setatrr__, __delattr__ (still need some work)

Update __call__ method of the SeasonalParameter class.

The __call__ method of the SeasonalParameter class is not inherited from its base class anymore.  This is due to the methods input can be defined via keyword arguments only.

Add doctests to the SeasonalParameter class.

Now the doctests should reflect the current status of the class.

Enable the Ellipsis option of the doctest module.

This allows for writing "..." instead of a certain output. For example, this is convenient in cases where the standard exception messages of Python 2 and 3 are different.

Add property "timeofyear" to the Indexer class of module indextools.

"timeofyear" index arrays are supposed to support the handling of SeasonalParameter instances.  They map the current simulation step to the index of a simulation step in a reference year.

Note that the unittests capture the basic functionalities. But they a just adaptions of the unittests of "dayofyear" index array.

Allow for a time dependence of the actual values of "SeasonalParameter" instances.

The class `SeasonalParameter` did not use the method `applytimefactor` so far. This bug has now been fixed. But note that this bug has only been detected by a doctest of the base model llake. So a more rigorous testing of the `SeasonalParameter` class itself seems advisable.

Replace module `lake_links` by the modules `lake_inlets` and `lake_outlets`.

Seperating into two modules gives the advantage of two different namespaces. So two different link sequence classes `Q` could be defined. The inlet sequence class `Q` is now 1-dimensional, allowing for multiple inflows into one lake. The outlet sequence class 'Q' is still 0-dimensional.

Add the `VQ` class to module llake_fluxes.

VQ is just an auxiliary term. But it can be very usefull to keep track of its behaviour over time, to understand the functioning of the llake model. Hence it is derived from the `FluxSequence` class instead of the `AidSequence` class.

Let the `MaxDW` class inherit from `SeasonalParameter` instead of `SingleParameter`.

Due to this change, abstractions from (or additions to) the calculated lake outflow can vary over time.

A thought for later: Principally, this change could be applied on many model parameters, increasing their flexibilitly, but not requiring changes in their original usage.

Fix a bug in the 'SeasonalParameter` class doctests (module `parametertools`).

Originally, I exchanged the class property `simulationstep` with a class member of type `Period`, which had some side effects.

Implement option "warnmissingcontrolfile".

Beforehand, a missing control file generally resulted in an exception abording the whole model initialization procedure.  Now, the user can set the option "warnmissingcontrolfile" of class Options of module "objecttools" to True. Then the mentioned exception is catched in method "initmodels" of the HydPy class, and only a warning is raised.

Implement option "checkseries".

Beforehand, one had always to make sure that the whole initialization period was completely covered by the required input data of all selected models. Otherwise, an error was raised, aborting the whole time series initialization procedure.

Usually, this is a save and useful strategy. But there are situations, where one for example wants to extend the initialization period into the future, but be able to add new input date when they become available.

To allow this, the property "checkseries" of the "Option" class of module "objecttools" has been implementend.  Additionally,  the method "load_ext" of the "IOSequence" class of module "sequencetools" has been extended.

Note that some refactoring of method "load_ext" might be advisable. And it of greatest importance to add some unit tests, as the associated indexing opperations are generally error prone!

Allow to initialize a project with a missing main file.

Main files became less and less important. In fact, I don't use them any more. It lead to much more reproducible code when things like the simulation time period are directly noted in the scripts defining the workflow.

So I decided to make main files optional simply by catching the related IOError silently. It would be better to add raise a warning, when a main file is missing...

Increase the numerical accuracy of HydPy-L-Lake.

L-Lake was solved with a fixed time step size equal to the simulation step size.  This commit adds the control parameter `MaxDT`, which allows to define a inner calculation step size smaller than the outer simulation step size.  Some additional changes are necessary:

 - The new derived parameter `NmbSubsteps` represents the integer fraction of the outer and the inner step size.
 - The auxiliary variable `VQ` does now inherit from `AideSequences`.
 - The iteration method `calc_vq_v1` is introduced and methods `calc_vq_v1` and `calc_v_qa_v1` are adapted.

Add function `autodoc_basemodel` to module `magictools`.

The function `autodoc_basemodel` can be called in `__init__` modules of base model packages. It adds some reStructuredText lines into the module docstring, which links to the other modules and specific classes of the base model packages. This helps in building the online documentation of HydPy in a more automated manner.

Add function `description` to module `objecttools`.

The function `description` clears up and returns the first paragraph of the docstring of the given object.

Add reStructuredText links in classes inheriting from `Model`.

The meta class `MetaModelClass` of module `modeltools` now appends links referencing the selected `run methods` and `additional methods` of base models and application models.

Define meta classes for classes `Parameter` and `Sequence` of modules `parametertools` and `sequencetools`.

Both meta classes check if the required class attributes `_PARCLASSES` or `_SEQCLASSES` are defined respectively.  They also add reStructuredText of the classes contained in the respective tuples to the docstring of the classes `Parameters` or `Sequences` respectively.

Add a string representation to class `Parameters` of module `parametertools`.

The string representation is consistent with the one of class `Sequences` of module `sequencetools`.

Make the seperate definition of the classes `Parameters` and `Sequences` in base and application models optional.

So  far, one always had to define a new class for each new model, simply inheriting from the base class made available by the modules `parametertools` or `sequencetools` respectively, often without adding any additional features.  Now this has to be done only, when one really wants to implement additional features.

Introduce `_INT_NAN` as a module level constant of module `objecttools`.

The value `-999999` is thought to be used instead of `nan` for integer values.

Introduce the `usedefaultvalues` property as an additional property of class `Options` of module `objecttools`.

In favour of reproducibility, this option is set to `False` by default, meaning the default values of parameters (class attribute `INIT`) are ignored.

Introduce the `initvalue` property of class `Parameter` and class `Sequence`.

`initvalue` returns the default parameter value or the default initial condition value definit by the class attribute `INIT`, if the `usedefaultvalues` option is set to `True`.  If this option is set to False, appropriate missing value representations are returned. If the option and set to True and not `INIT` attribute exists, the behaviour of `initvalue` differs.  For parameters, the appropriate missing value representation is returned.  For sequences, zero is returned.

This commits also changes some other methods  and doctests related to the introduction of the `initvalue` property.

Revise method `trim` of module `objecttools`.

This commits makes the `trim` method more flexible.

The first major change is that floating point and integer values are now handled in a different manner. For floating point values, the old trimming with optional warning messages is performed. For integer values, exceptions are raised instead.

The second major change is that missing values can now be handled properly.  Comparing a value with e.g. a lower boundary with a `nan` value does not result in any trimming, warnings or exceptions. For example, this offers more flexibility in defining the order in which the values of different, related parameters are set.

Simplify the `trim` methods of the control parameters defined in module `lland_control'.

The simplifications are possible due to commit #0e5be43.

Handle pure Python model functions as instance methods instead of class methods.

Before this commit, model functions were added to the model class itself via a metaclass.  Now these functions are explicitely converted to methods and connected to model objects during their initialization. This strategy is more consistent with the handling of parameter and sequence objects and their respective collection classes. Due to this commit, the automatically generated documentation of application models is more consistent.

This configuration package is thought for bundling additional configuration data of different types.  Arbitrary file formats are allowed.

Generalize `setup.py`.

The changes are primarilly supposed to ease further framework development.  The related changes are:

 * New packages do not need be mentioned in setup.py.  Instead, all packages are identified automatically.

 * The same is true for new Cython extension modules.

 * All filed from the new `conf` packages are copied to the site-packages folder.

Additionally, compiled Cython `pyd` files are copied from the site-package folder to the original installation folder.  Hence framework or model developers are not required to do it manually.

Use the `nogil` in cythonized models where possible.

Releasing Python's Global Interpreter Lock might have three advantages:

* Faster calculations through more rigorous inlining by the C compiler

* Faster calculations through multi-threading - if one implements this later...

* Faster calculations through not missing Python objects in Cython methods.  If one does so when defining a new hydrological model, a nogil error is raised...

Improve the handling  `Element` and `Node` object names.

As other objects in HydPy, instances of the classes `Element` and `Node` know their own name.  Also, elements and nodes are usually accessed as attributes of instances of their collection classes `Elements` and `Nodes` (and as attributes of `Connections` instances).

To ensure that the attribute names and element names (or node names) remained consistent, it was not allowed to change the name of any element or node.  (The same is true for parameters and sequences).

This was sufficient for using already finished network structures. But it made it very hard to construct new network structures or to change existing ones.

Now some strategies are implemented which allow for changing the names of elements and nodes while keeping the whole network structure consistent.

By the way, also new `__iter__` methods are defined. Now, only the element or node is returned when iterating `Elements`, `Nodes`, or `Connections` objects instead of (name, element) or (name, node) tuples.

Add docstring substitution capabilities to module `autodoctools`.

Defining links using Sphinx text roles is hard to read for deeply nested package structures.  The commen Sphinx substitutions can be in conflict with Sphinx's Python roles (e.g. :class:).  This commit introduces an alternative substitution mechanism, also based on the "|something|" syntax.  This has the benefit that, when a substitution cannot be resolved, a warning is raised by Sphinx automatically.

This (too) large commit is thought for prepare the HydPy 2.0.0 release.

What this commit does:
 * Make all user relevant features importable from the `hydpy` package directly.
 * Let doctests import required objects directly from `hydpy`, and not from the module in which they are defined.
 * Make all user relevant names more consistent (e.g. `plot_fluxes` instead of `fluxplot`).
 * Introduce some sequence container related abstract base classes.
 * Remove the old `MainManager` class from module `filetools`.  It had not been used for a long time and was a potential way of trouble regarding reproducibility, as it allowed to define some configurations in an external file that could be easily written in a workflow script.
 * Simplify the project directory structure.
 * Refactor and standardize the classes of module `filetools` by introducing the base class `FileManager`
 * Change the iteration over parameter and sequence collections. Now, only the parameters and sequences themselves are yielded, not tuples containing both their names and themselves. This is more consistent with other collections and allows for a cleaner code base.

With version 2.0.0, Sphinx needs to run twice on Travis. See issue  mcmtroffaes/sphinxcontrib-bibtex#214.

This is what I tried to get it running (the first command is allowed to fail, the second not):
  - if [ $TRAVIS_PYTHON_VERSION == "3.7" ] ; then travis-sphinx build  --source=hydpy/docs/auto || true; fi
  - if [ $TRAVIS_PYTHON_VERSION == "3.7" ] ; then travis-sphinx build  --source=hydpy/docs/auto; fi

However, the second command also fails, as Sphinx cannot find the `bibtex.json` file generated in the first run.
I suspect, this is due to how the `travis-sphinx` script works.

Add the modules `quadtools` and `quadutils`.

The implemented "Quad" classes help to define submodels that perform numerical integrations via Gau-Lobatto quadrature. There is much room left for optimisation, but it at least works. We show this for the toy method `Calc_DVEq_V1` of base model `wland`, which we can use for later optimisations.

One simple improvement would be to remember the number of nodes required in the last integration run, to not always start with the lowest number of nodes allowed.

This commit silences pylint and avoids `EncodingWarning` problems in the future (see PEP 597). For backward compatibility, "locale" would have been the correct choice.  However, for cross-platform compatibility, the selected "utf-8" should be better. Hopefully, this does not make a big difference because HydPy rarely (never?) reads or writes non-ASCII characters so far.
Minor adjustments to satisfy pylint.
Use "priority levels" to allow for shorter substitution names (module `autodoctools`).

Introduce piecewise linear and spline interpolation as alternatives to neural network-based interpolation.

Also, it moves class `SeasonalANN` from module `anntools` to `interptools` and renames it to `SeasonalInterpolator`.  Finally, it should adjust all parts of the documentation concerning interpolation "within" model methods to clarify that users are now free to select the interpolation algorithm of their choice.

Add class `MultiplyIUH` to module `calibtools`.

We need to change this because we want to prevent importing features from the `models` subpackages into the modules defined in the `auxs` subpackage.  We should either move `ReplaceIUH` and `MultiplyIUH` to the `arma` model or define a `Responses` base class in a module somewhere in the `auxs` subpackage.

Fix class `LinearStorageCascade` of module `iuhtools` for very high numbers of storages.

`LinearStorageCascade` now generally performs a logarithmic transformation, which prevents overflow errors for high numbers of storages.  In my tests, I did not encounter a case where this solution leads to less accurate results than the previous solution.

Remove some unused URLs from `README.rst`.

This change makes automatic calibration (where some parameter values might be temporarily "strange") more robust.
Fix a broken URL in `index.rst`.

Hence, I  refactored `make_rules` to clarify this limitation by stricter typing and decoupling rule objects' creation and handling. Enable the `useless-suppression` feature of pylint in `pylintrc` and use it for removing outdated "disable" statements.

Pylint now emits three false positives:
 *  I0021: Useless suppression of 'line-too-long' (useless-suppression) --> multiple times
 *  I0021: Useless suppression of 'wrong-import-position' (useless-suppression)  --> two times
 *  I0021: Useless suppression of 'wrong-import-position' (not-an-iterable)  --> one time

However, that is not a big problem as `useless-suppression` is not counted as an error and does not impact the final score. There are already some related open issues on GitHub.

Improve the typing of class `CalibrationInterface` of module `calibtools`.

The small change in the related type variables allows defining `CalibrationInterface` instances handling different `Rule` objects, for example `CalibrationInterface[Union[Replace, Add]]`. (I do not know why this works with bound but not with constraint type variables.)
Add argument `legend` to method `plot` of class `SeasonalInterpolator` of module `interptools` (flag to enable/disable the automatic creation of a legend within the plot).

Allow multiple instances of application model `exch_v001` target the same (e.g. `dam_v006`) model instance.

Assume there are three lakes (l1, l2, and l3) and two exchange models (e1 and e2).  e1 connects l1 with l2 and e2 connects l2 with l3.  Until now, this does not work, as we can (and want to) define only one exchange node (and one water level node) per lake model instance and method `Pass_ActualExchange_V1` overwriting values of those exchange nodes.  With this commit, method `Pass_ActualExchange_V1` adds or substracts the exchange from the respective nodes so that results from the previously processed exchange model are preserved, and everything should work as expected.

Improve method `update_ar_coefs` of class `ARMA` of module `armatools` for when the turning point detection fails.

The ARMA coefficients now fall back to the original MA coefficients in such cases.  This change completes commit #add326497550b8898857fd64ab08676f82fed19d.

Add the flux sequence `SR` (sealed surface runoff) to base model `hland` and all its application models.

Improve the snow redistribution approach implemented in base model `hland`  and all its application models.

The simple snow redistribution approach aims to prevent the formation of "snow towers" in high elevation zones in mountainous catchments.  The old implementation works but can have the undesired side-effect of forming "snow towers" in the lowest zones of such catchments.  We knew this could theoretically happen but thought this would not happen in reality.  Experience in an alpine catchment in Switzerland showed we were wrong.

In the revised approach, we avoid this problem by a "from bottom to top" re-redistribution. The implementation is a little complicated, but the results are sensible.  To make this work, we needed to exclude all internal lake zones from participating in snow redistribution (which might be a good choice anyway).

Tidy up HydPy build and test processes.

HydPy's build process was highly outdated and intermixed with parts of the test processes.  This commit highly both concerns and eases manual execution.

The key improvements:
 * Use `build` as the front end for building HydPys source distribution and wheels (instead of `setuptools`).
 * Do not use `distutils` anymore.
 * Use `nox` to execute all kinds of tests.
 * Use `lastversion?  to let `pynsist` install the dependencies by itself.
 * Tidy up the install commands in `.travis.yml` and `appveyor.yml` (made possible by the improvements listed beforehand).
 * Improve the site customisation process to ensure the correctness of code coverage measurements for subprocesses (and on different operating systems).
 * Improve the robustness and configurability of the doctest routines.
 * Set USEAUTODOC to False by default (I should remove it later completely).
 * Simplify `setup.py` (e.g. by moving parts into `prepare_build.py`).
 * Fix `Manifest.in` and make it more explicit.
 * Move some scripts from the base path to the `docs` and `tests` sub-packages.
 * Rename subpackage `bibliography` to `bib`.
 * Rename script `test_everything.py` to `run_doctests.py`.
 * Exclude `modelutils.py` from code coverage measurements (because building and testing are now separated; reverse this later?)
 * Remove `make.bat` and `Makefile` (which were only required for preparing the initial Sphinx configuration, if I remember correctly).
Some documentation updates (primarily related to the new build process, also some typo fixes).

Remove the NetCDF related options `flatten` and `timeaxis`.

From now on, reading and writing NetCDF files always works like setting `flatten` to `True` and `timeaxis` to 0. Enabling `flatten` circumvents defining partially incomplete arrays when working with sequences of different shapes.  Using the first axis for time agrees with the NetCDF-CF metadata conventions.  Also, it is the only reasonable choice for reading or writing data "just in time" during a simulation run.      We decided to fix these settings to ease the implementation of the "just in time" functionalities and other upcoming NetCDF related improvements.  Simpler usability was also a relevant point for introducing this backwards-incompatible change.

Remove the NetCDF related option `isolate`.

From now on, reading and writing NetCDF files always works like setting `isolate` to `True`.  We decided to fix this setting to shorten the documentation, improve usability, and ease the implementation of upcoming NetCDF related improvements.

Removing the `isolate` option allowed us to significantly simplify module `netcdftools`.  Most importantly, we could remove class `NetCDFFile`.  Now, `NetCDFInterface` collect  all required `NetCDFVariable` instances without a need to use `NetCDFFile` instances as interlayers.

Store time series data in a single directory by default.

Until now, class `SequenceManager` was unique, as it handled three default directories: "input" for all model-specific input sequences, "output" for all model-specific output sequences, and "node" for all node sequences.  This functionality was inconsistent with the single `currentdir` inherited from class `FileManager`, and assigning values to this property had no effect.  Also, the separation between the different directories became unclear due to adding writing features to the input sequences and the increasingly ambiguous nature of the node sequences.  Hence, consistently to handling the control files, we decided to store all time series in a directory named "default" from now on.   The user can either temporarily change the directory for all sequences via property `currentdir` or define individual paths for different sequence objects via the new `dirpath` property of class `IOSequences`.

This commit also updates the XML support and addresses the issue of reading time-series data from and writing time-series data to different directories "just in time" during a SINGLE simulation run.   We leave the handling of MULTIPLE runs for a later commit.  We need to rework the related features more thoroughly due to the requirement to change directories (temporarily) from the client-side for data assimilation.

Support "manual" reading and writing of time-series via the HydPy server.

Regarding reading: The user can now disable the automatic reading of the required input series during the server start. Instead, he can register alternative directories and instruct the HydPy server to read from these directories when the server is ready.

Regarding writing: Before this commit, the client needed to query simulation results and save them by himself. From now on, the client can register alternative directories and instruct the HydPy server to write into these directories.

Both features work for "normal" and "just in time" writing. We implemented them to improve the efficiency of working with meteorological forecasts and the flexibility when working with data assimilation tools.

I am not entirely sure this is a good idea because of possible side effects.  The only potential problem I found concerns the "index array" defined by module `indextools`.  This one is fixed, but we need some experimentation to ensure the new functionality does not break other things.

Define a HydPy reference style and a HydPy bibliography style.

This commit uses new features of sphinxcontrib-bibtex 2.4.2.  Besides these general technical changes, it cleans up the existing bibliography and homogenises the citations in the documentation on HydPy-Meteo and HydPy-Evap.
Fix or simplify the documented units of the class `RSchmelz`, `CPWasser`, `CPEis`, `LW`, and `LWE` and fix the Latex equation of class `Calc_SFF_V1` (base model `lland`).

Let method `query_timegrid` of module `netcdftools` only emit warnings for inconsistent global and file-specific information on the timestamp of NetCDF files, not when the NetCDF file does not define the timestamp.

Modifies commit b8da4b6d06b5aa50be2b609957ef92c6d9ff57ab.

Do not support defining the initialisation time grid via NetCDF files when using the XML support.

This feature was just a stop-gap, and we (hopefully) do not need it anymore.  Removing it simplifies the next commit.

Replace the HydPy-specific NetCDF attribute `timestampleft` with `timereference` for a more precise definition of the time reference of state sequences.

The supported values of `timereference` are `left interval boundary`, `right interval boundary`, and `current time`.  The name of the related global option is still `timestampleft`, and its type is still `bool`.  However, from now on, this option only affects "interval-related" time series like precipitation or (average) temperature but not states like soil moisture.

There are still some sequences like `WaterLevel` of the `dam` model (which is a factor sequence) that are also "point-related" but handled as "interval-related".  We have to find a way to deal with these exceptional non-state sequences later.

Add the methods `POST_register_outputcontroldir`, `GET_deregister_outputcontroldir`, `GET_query_outputcontroldir`, and `GET_save_controls` to class `HydPyServer` of module `servertools` for saving (calibrated) model parameters.

Remove the critical discussion regarding potential differences of `hland_v1` to the original `HBV96` implementation.

Finally, we found out the problems in some subcatchments of the Main river were due to a configuration problem in the `HBV96`-based model and not due to differences in the model implementations.  Hence, its nothing that needs to be discussed in the HydPy documentation.
Move the exceptions defined in method `__call__` of class `Parameter` of module `parametertools` into individual methods.

Add method `_find_kwargscombination` to class `Parameter` of module `parametertools` and use it to refactor (and slightly improve) class `SFDist` of base model `hland`.

This is the first step in a stronger standardisation of the handling of keyword arguments in `__call__` methods of  `Parameter` subclasses.

Add function `trim_kwarg` to module `parametertools` for trimming keyword arguments similar to positional arguments when setting parameter values.

This commit supplements commit 4a4470aa7dfe34d6ae69cbc31d3947a2b80ddb80, but much needs to be done.
Make an exception message of class `Variable` of module `variabletools` related to math operations compatible with doctesting.

Do not let class `MixinFixedShape` of module `variabletools` raise an error when trying to redefine the same shape as defined beforehand.

This change allows deep copies of `Variable` subclasses that rely on `MixinFixedShape`.

Move application model `hstream_v1` to the new model family `HydPy-Musk`, rename it to `musk_classic`, and make its parametrisation more flexible.

This commit became much larger than expected.  We use `hstream_v1`/`musk_classic` in many doctests, which all needed to be adapted.  Furthermore, the more flexible way to define the Muskingum coefficients (based on keyword arguments) made calibration with the tools of modules `calibtools`, `itemtools`, and `xmltools` impossible.  Hence, we needed to make some progress  on how to handle the calibration of parameters via keyword arguments in general.  We added the `Parameter` class attribute `KEYWORDS` as a standardisation attempt and improved the `keywordarguments` property.  Looking at the doctests, we seem to be going in a good direction, but there are still many pitfalls left, and we still need to fill the `KEYWORDS` tuple for all relevant `Parameter` subclasses besides those of `musk_classic`.

Mask a problematic usage of `NotImplemetedError` by class `Parameter` of module `parametertools` to trick pylint.

I added a ToDo...
Adjust the names of some type variables to recent pylint changes (see https://github.com/PyCQA/pylint/issues/5981).
Start supporting Python 3.10.

Add a few `pylint: disable=not-callable` statements where we "call" options to change them temporarily.

The number of false positives depends not only on the versions of `pylint` and `astropy` but also on the version of `Python`.  Therefore, we should add such disable statements to all potentially problematic lines until this `pylint` bug is fixed.

Fix the "get_condition" feature of class `IntegrationTest` of module `testtools` for querying the very first condition (before starting the simulation run) or the very last condition (after finishing the simulation run).

Add application model `musk_mct` to the `HydPy-Musk` model family.

`musk_mct` required a new model base class, which also comes with this commit `SegmentModel`.

We want to allow framework users to control the accuracy of the Pegasus iteration included in `musk_mct`.  Therefore, this commit also adds the feature to define "method-specific" solver parameters.

We should improve two things later:

 * The prevention of negative discharges (the existing approach works but introduces water balance errors and unrealistic discharge fluctuations).

 * The default accuracy of the Pegasus iteration (we need to adapt it to the catchment size).
Add the `.nox` directory to `.gitignore`.
Disable pylint's `too-many-ancestors` check (`pylintrc`).
Add XML support for loading selections from alternative network directories via the new XML element `network_io`.

Cythonize application model `dummy_v1`.

So far, `dummy_v1` was only available in Python mode, and its base model `dummy` crashed in Cython mode.

Use the catchment size for calculating the error tolerance of the estimation of the reference water level of application model `musk_mct`.

The approach is similar to the one implemented in all `dam` models.  I hope it increases computation speed significantly without decreasing accuracy too much.  We should evaluate this in some real projects and eventually refine the strategy later.

Support reading NetCDF files generated by Delft-FEWS when working with ensembles, including an (unnecessary) dimension called `realizations` (module `netcdftools`).

This commit covers reading data into RAM and reading and writing data "just in time".  The data import of Delft-FEWS never requires a `realizations` dimension, so supporting an option for adding such a dimension when writing data from RAM seems like a useless complication.

Fix method `check_waterbalance` of application models `lland_v3` and `lland_v4`.

So far, both methods did not consider snow evaporation for "non-soil" land-use classes like "GLACIER".

Improve some warnings related to reading NetCDF files (module `netcdftools`).

 * mention the correct filename instead of `/`
 * Delft-FEWS writes `realization` instead of `realizations` (see commit 54f04dd1503effa438be70e946cd3f62284c1ddc)

Improve method `Calc_In_WC_V1` of base model `hland`.

The new formulation guarantees that `WC` never exceeds the product of `WHC` and `SP`.  Previously, tiny violations due to limited numerical precision led to unnecessary `trim` warnings.
Remove script `modify_html.py`, which does not work correctly for a while now.

Fix the documentation of class `Options` of module `optiontools`.

The descriptor-based attributes' docstrings were missing due to not handling class attribute access properly.

Add the factor sequence `SWE`(snow water equivalent)  to the base model `hland` and all its application models.

This addition does not change how hland's snow routine works.  Instead, it is just for convenience.  Users can now access (time series of) the total snow water equivalent directly, which is helpful in the contexts of data assimilation and parameter calibration.

Make the format of the `subnames` of exchange items (module `itemtools`) more consistent with the format of the `subdevicenames` within NetCDF files (module `netcdftools`).

Generally, consistency is a good thing.  However, the specific purpose of this commit is to simplify coupling HydPy with OpenDA when one prefers to read non-scalar observation time series from NetCDF files.

Fix the XML support for exchanging time series via `SetItem` objects (modules `xmltools` and `itemtools`).

Previously, the preparation of the `series` attribute of the relevant `IOSequence` objects crashed because it required that the `series` attribute is already prepared.  Our tests did not detect this bug.  The `series` attribute was already prepared in all cases due to other reasons (reading or writing functionality configured under `series_io`).
Improve the type hint of the `timegrids` descriptor of the global `pub` module (`Timegrid` objects are valid setter types).
Remove method `__getattr__` from class `Model` of module `modeltools` for clearer "static" error messages when accessing unavailable attributes.

Reduce the initialisation time of "seasonal" model parameters depending on `TOY` objects.

The initialisation time of dam models using plenty of "time of year" nodes for defining very detailed seasonal patterns could take up to several minutes.  This problem was due to repeated, unnecessary sortings in method `refresh` of class `SeasonalParameter` of module `parametertools`, a very buggy hashing function of class `TOY` of module `timetools`, and a few related problems.

Add method `GET_deregister_internalconditions` to class `HydPyServer` of module `servertools`.

The implemented method helps save RAM and so supports performing data assimilations over long periods in huge projects.

Let the HydPy server support so-called "output items" (module `servertools` and `xmltools`).

Recently, we discovered that OpenDA is rather restricted when working with (multi-dimensional) exchange items used for observations.  Circumventing this limitation with our "getitem" mechanism proved difficult.  Hence, we extended the relevant parts of the usual "setitem" mechanism for factor sequences and states.  Corresponding adjustments in the OpenDA adapter split the data of the related 2-dimensional exchange items into multiple 1-dimensional exchange items.  We need to gain some experience with this stopgap.  If it works well, we will at least adjust some terms in HydPy (outputitems, OutputSequence, SetItem, GetItem...) to restore consistency.
Update version number.
Minor adjustments in module `calibtools`.
Fix the documentation on parameter `K4` of base model `hland`.
Fix a type in the figure of `hland_v4` (write `QVs1` and `QVs2` instead of `TVs1` and `TVs1`).
Fix a wrong title in `refs.bib`.
Fix the `trim` method of class `SP` (snow pack) of base model `hland` for zero `WHC` values (zero water holding capacity).

Improve the speed of method `update_devices` of class `HydPy` of module `hydpytools`.

For large projects, the improvement is huge.
Refactor a few methods of class `HydPyServer` of module `servertools`.
Let class `HydPyServer` of module `servertools` support the new "Particle Filter workflow" of the HydPy-OpenDA adapter.
Adjust the code to pylint 2.14.
Add pylint to `requirements.txt`.

Add some "pylint: disable=not-callable" statements because pylint does not seem to understand the implementation of the  attributes of class `Options` of module `optionstools`  well enough.

For Python 3.8, this problem occurs on Travis (Linux) but not on my local machine (Windows). Maybe related to #PyCQA/pylint/3068?
Update version number.
Complete the type hints of module `filetools` (which requires making class `InfoArray` of module `sequencetools` more type-safe).
Add the context manager methods `netcdfreading` and `netcdfwriting` to class `SequenceManager` to module `sequencetools`.

Make class `Variable` of module `variabletools` non-generic (and improve some more or less related typing issues).

This change adds a little boilerplate code to the subclasses of `Variable`.  However, it helps to avoid recursive type definitions which Mypy cannot handle currently).  Furthermore, type narrowing of `Variable` subclasses in scripts (especially for `IOSequence`) is now much more convenient.

There a some problems with documenting the attributes `subvars`, `subpars`, and `subseqs`.  For now, we exclude them from the documentation completely.

Finish the type hints of module `devicetools`.

Typing the hidden registries could be better, but it is probably not worth the effort.  Also, the annotations of the `__new__` methods are not very precise and I need to bind the TypeVar `TypesDevices` to `Devices[Any]`.  Maybe, this is inevitable due to current Mypy limitations (missing "higher kind of types" support)?  However, it's all very low priority at the moment, but I left some ToDos in the case we must revisit these issues later.
Add a missing import of `Literal` in module `masktools` (only available in `typing_extensions` for Python 3.7.).

Adjust the `update` method of parameter `W0` of base model `hland` to recent numpy changes.

So far, I filtered "divide by zero encountered in true_divide" warnings, but the new literal seems to be "divide by zero encountered in divide".
Fix a wrong import order in module `masktools` (fixes e4cb9c70d96a4ece7b71044382a0bd1c025524d1).
Define the packages to be inserted explicitely in `setup.py`.

Adjust the context manager `provide_jitaccess` of class `NetCDFInterface` of module `netcdftools` to NetCDF4 1.6.

NetCDF4 now creates a new Dataset in the `r+` mode if one does not already exist.  This change resulted in the creation of incomplete NetCDF files and subsequent incomprehensible error messages.  `provide_jitaccess` now raises a `FileNotFound` error on its own, when appropriate.
Remove an unnecessary import of the `typing` module from module `quadutils`, which results in the error 2106 ('=' : left operand must be l-value) when workings with Cython 0.29.31.
Use `round_` throughout all likelihood function doctests in module `statstools`.

Improve the process of installing HydPy for testing to work when environment markers are used (script `noxfile`).

The current solution should be more stable and, like the old approach, ensure we do not test a wrong HydPy version (loaded from PyPI) by accident.

Do not install netCDF4 1.6 or newer versions under Python 3.7.

netCDF4 1.6 is still compatible with Python 3.7 but requires a higher installation effort. See https://github.com/Unidata/netcdf4-python/issues/1174.

Support the type annotation ": float" to define the C type `double` in model methods (module `modelutils)`.

This (fixed) annotation makes the code more readable than prefixing "d_".  It would be favourable to get rid of the old prefixing approach later.

Improve how `lland` models runoff concentration.

See issue #87 for a thorough explanation.
Update version number.
Fix and extend the type hints of the cython extension classes `Double` and `PDouble` of module `pointerutils`.
Tidy up the bibliography (especially: prefer DOI over URL - it looks a little confusing when both types of links are available for the same reference).
Minor documentation fixes for base model `wland`.
Improve class `IntegrationTest` of module `testtools` for cases where the simulation period does not span the whole initialisation period.

Use the ELLIPSIS doctest flag in method `add_module` of class `Substituter` of module `autodoctools` to hide that the method `get_role` under returns `const` instead of `class` for `NDArrayFloat` of module `typingtools` under rare occassions (Python 3.8, Windows, AppVeyor).
Fix c623251c61dc5622a28402c66d27352d33a0c58f, so that all entries of the list of the available documentation versions are placed in separate lines (script `combine_docversions.py`).
Improve class `IntegrationTest` of module `testtools` for cases where the simulation period does not span the whole initialisation period (completes commit 7bb72f68214e1230cc1861b9da5730340fa001b3).
Let function `check_selectedvariables` of module `testtools` not report missing "UPDATESEQUENCES" if its submethods select them as "UPDATESEQUENCES" but the method itself as "RESULTSEQUENCES".

Replace `bool` with `numpy.npy_bool` instead of `bint` when cythonizing models (module `modelutils`).

This change allows defining boolean arrays for handling the values of 1-dimensional parameter classes or sequence classes.
Remove some definitions of standard type variables already available in the `typingtools` module.

Add the Green-Ampt model family `ga` and its first application model `ga_garto`.

According to our testing, `ga_garto` works as it should.  However, there are still some open questions regarding the GARTO algorithm itself and on coupling it to HydPy-L and other "complete" hydrological models (see the related GitHub issues).  Hence, we might need to adjust `ga_garto` later.
Add the cython module `interfaceutils`, which implements the single base type `BaseInterface` for casting purposes (topic: submodel modularisation).
Let script `prepare_build` cythonize all available submodel interfaces (topic: submodel modularisation).

Add the base class `SubmodelInterface` to module `modeltools` and make it usable in pure Python mode (topic: submodel modularisation).

This change introduces the new model class attribute `SUBMODELINTERFACES`, which must be added to all currently available model classes.
Add basic support for cythonizing models relying on the new submodel modularisation concept (module `modelutils`).

Add class `SubmodelProperty` to module `modeltools` and apply it automatically during model class initialisation for connecting main models with submodels.

The implemented support for building the connections targets the scripting level.  Support for building connections within control files is still missing.
Add the parameter `conjunction` to function `enumeration` of module `objecttools` to allow replacing "and" with "or", for example.
Allow base model `lland` using submodels following the `SoilSubmodel_V1` interface for more detailed calculations of direct runoff and groundwater recharge (topic: submodel modularisation).
Add the `interfaces` subpackage and the prototype submodel interface `SoilModel_V1` in the new module `soilinterfaces` (topic: submodel modularisation).
Add all methods to the `ga` base model required to satisfy the `SoilModel_V1` interface (topic: submodel modularisation).
Support to couple the application model `lland_v1` with submodels following the `SoilModel_V1` interface (topic: submodel modularisation).
Support to couple the application model `lland_v2` with submodels following the `SoilModel_V1` interface (topic: submodel modularisation).
Support to couple the application model `lland_v3` with submodels following the `SoilModel_V1` interface (topic: submodel modularisation).
Support to couple the application model `lland_v4` with submodels following the `SoilModel_V1` interface (topic: submodel modularisation).
Use `evalseries` instead of the `series` attribute for checking the water balance of application models `lland_v1`, `lland_v2`, `lland_v3`, and `lland_v4`.
Add the submodel `ga_garto_submodel1` (topic: submodel modularisation).

Allow adding control, derived, or fixed parameters to specific models by the new model attributes `ADDITIONAL_CONTROLPARAMETERS`, `ADDITIONAL_DERIVEDPARAMETERS`, and `ADDITIONAL_FIXEDPARAMETERS`.

The reason for implementing this simple (but a little hidden) feature is that users currently require the control parameter `NmbBins` to prepare the 1-dimensional variables of `ga_garto_submodel1` conveniently, but none of the submodels' methods selects it.
Do not install pylint 2.15 because of the errors reported in issues `https://github.com/PyCQA/pylint/issues/7428` and `https://github.com/PyCQA/pylint/issues/7433`.
Update version number: 6.0a0
Do not inline interface methods when cythonizing submodels (module `modelutils`, topic: submodel modularisation).
Add two `  #disable=not-callable` comments to module `armatools` to fix false pylint warnings.
Fix two minor typing issues in module `calibtools`.
Fix passing an application model's module to the constructor of class `Rule` of module `calibtools`.

Speed up the `__call__` methods of class `TranslationDiffusionEquation` and `LinearStorageCascade` of module `iuhtools` for given scalar time points to optimise numerical integration based on scipy's `integrade.quad` method.

Improve "item access" and disallow "item assignment" of `Devices` objects (module `devicetools`).

* `0` is now a valid index for querying the single device handled by a `Devices` instance.
* Disallowing item assignment increases consistency with how we support attribute assignment.

Turn the `DefaultProperty` `currentpath` of class `FileManager` of module `filetools` into a pure getter property.

We now enforce setting absolute paths also by property `currentdir` (and explain it in the documentation).

Unfortunately, this change is not backwards compatible.  However, we found the alternate usage of `currentdir` and `currentpath` to result in confusion (and errors) in projects with large code bases.

Remove the `forceiterable` functionality from class `Devices` of module `devicetools`.

After introducing method `search_keywords`, the (inconvenient and seldom used) `forceiterable` functionality became obsolete.

Make attribute `mutable` of class `Devices` private and add the parameter `force` to methods `add_device` and `remove_device` as a surrogate.

Breaks backward compatibility unfortunately, but results in much cleaner client code.

Support "station names" with Unicode characters in NetCDF files (module `netcdftools`).

To my knowledge, NetCDF-CF restricts us from using ASCII characters, which is inconvenient when working in countries which's languages frequently use different characters.  So we decided to support the UTF-8 encoding.  Therefore, we split characters requiring more than one byte on multiple array entries.  This decision does not raise compatibility issues with other NetCDF-CF software as long as the user refrains from using non-ASCII characters.  And if the prefers to use non-ASCII characters, we can at least be confident that some other tools can cope with it (we checked this for `https://www.unidata.ucar.edu/downloads/netcdf-java/`).
Rename application model `evap_v001` to `evap_fao56`.
Fix the doctest of the derived parameter `SoilAreaFraction` of base model `ga`.
Add the `find_submodels` method to class `Model` of module `modeltools` and use it to allow `InputSequence` and `OutputSequence` instances to load and save time series data during simulation runs.
Let model developers apply class `SubmodelProperty` of module `modeltools` directly to allow using the same interface for different submodels.

Complete the "prepare_...series", "load_...series", and "save_...series" logic for class `Element` and `Elements` of module `devicetools` and class `Model` of module `modeltools`, taking the new submodel functionalities into account.
Automatise the input and output node connection mechanism for submodels.
Add module `petinterfaces` to the `interfaces` subpackage.

Let HydPy-Evap follow the submodel concept.

Things are still moving, but the following changes work for now:
 * `evap_fao56` now calculates a vector of reference evapotranspiration values, works as a submodel and a stand-alone model, and still provides a scalar output (now `MeanReferenceEvapotranspiration`) for building input/output node connections.
 * The first version of the application model `evap_tw2002` applies the Turc-Wendling method like `lland_v1` does.
 * Both models support adjusting the air temperature for individual hydrological response units.
  * The first version of the application model `evap_io` reads available reference evapotranspiration time series from files as `lland_v2` does.
Merge application models lland_v1` and `lland_v2` by supporting submodels following the `PETModel_V1` interface.

Add the submodels `petmodel` and `pemodel` to application models `wland_v001` and `wland_v002` for calculating reference evapotranspiration and potential water evaporation independently.

Reference evapotranspiration must be 1-dimensional, but potential water evaporation must be 0-dimensional.  Hence, this commit also adds the `Get_MeanReferenceEvapotranspiration` method to the `PETModel_V1` interface defined in module `petinterfaces` and adjusts all `evap` submodels.
Support Python 3.11, drop Python 3.7, finally stop using `bokeh`, and tidy up all requirements.
Do not reference the `assert_never` function of module `objecttools` by a substitution since Python 3.11 provides the same function.

Adjust a few things so that pylint 2.15 does not complain when running with Python 3.11, and remove all imports from `typing_extensions` and some non-wildcard imports from `typing`, which (hopefully) become obsolete after dropping support for Python 3.7.

Principally, we now could remove `typing_extensions` from our requirements.  However, it is lightweight, and we will likely use some of its other features soon, so I prefer to leave it in for convenience.

Adjust methods `search_upstream` and `search_downstream` of class `Selection` of module `selectiontools` to recent changes in `networkx` (the functions `ancestors` and `descendants` now require the graph as a positional argument).
Remove method `_ignore` from class `LogFileInterface` of module `commandtools`, which is not required after dropping support for Python 3.7.
Use `setuptools` instead of (deprecated) `distutils` for cythonizing models "manually".
Use function `pkutil.iter_modules` instead of `pkutil.walk_packages` when importing all models to prevent loading `Lib.test` accidentally.
Use `numpy.random` instead of `numpy.warnings` (which does not exist anymore) as an example in the doctest of method `consider_member` of class `Substituter` of module `autodoctools`.
Adjust method `from_array` of class `Date` of module `timetools` and method `prepare_output_arrays` of class `UnitTest` of module `testtools` to avoid warnings about unsafe casting in numpy 1.24.
Increase consistency when declaring integers for cythonizing models.

Add default values for the `hland` control parameters according to the IHMS manual.

Additionally:
* Add package `wheel` to `pyproject.toml`.
* Fix the span tuple of state sequence `BW1` of application model `hland_v4`.
Install the latest version of `nsis` on AppVeyor and start the script function `run_doctests` by providing the full path to `hyd.py.exe`.

Let the `nox` session  `sphinx` remove the auto-generated `.doctrees` directory.

The concrete occasion for this change is that we accidentally pushed this directory to GitHub pages, but GitHub recently started to reject it because of too large file sizes.  However, I prefer to remove not in `combine_docversions.py` but directly at the end of the `sphinx` session, as this generally decreases the risk of distributing unnecessarily storage-intensive versions of the documentation.
Improve the type hints of and add some assertions to module `importtools`.

Tidy up the "model wildcard import logic" implemented in module `importtools`.

 * Separate model initialisation (still in function `parameterstep`) from making the user-relevant model attributes easily accessible as local variables (now in function "_add_locals_to_namespace").
 * Stop adding some objects as local variables which are not user-relevant model attributes.
 * Add the __HYDPY_MODEL_LOCALS__  dictionary to the local variables, which contains the local variables themself (except __HYDPY_MODEL_LOCALS__) to simplify later manipulations.

Add the decorator `abstractmodelmethod` to module `modeltools` to allow for distinctions between those abstract `Model` methods one can override statically and those one needs to add dynamically during model initialisation.

Modify class `SubmodelInterface` of module `modeltools`.

 * Remove the automatically determined `name` attribute (obsolete since commit b275e02ef71ae2ccf1fc01dc3622d3103f89c091).
 * Subclass from `Model` (so that Mypy is always aware that a submodel is a "normal" model).

Allow preparing submodels within a `with` block.

 * Add the decorator `prepare_submodel` to module `importtools`, which delegates the complex namespace logic to class `SubmodelAdder` and the model-specific setting of control parameters to the wrapped method.
 * Add the decorator `define_targetparameter` for wrapping the submodel-specific methods for preparing single parameters within `TargetParameterUpdater` instances.
 * Apply these new features to application model `lland_v1` and all application models of base model `evap` (so we have examples for testing).

Both classes expose information that will help improve consistency checks and write non-redundant control parameter files in later commits.

Adjust the code style to pylint 2.16.

 * Use dict literals instead of calls to `dict`.
 * Remove some obsolete disable statements.
 * Remove nested `max` calls.
 * Mark class `SubmodelInterface` of module `modeltools` explicitly as abstract.
Adjust the code style to black 23.1 (by removing unnecessary brackets and white lines).
Apply black and pylint separately on Travis.
Automatically update the derived parameters of the initialised submodel when leaving an `add_submodel` block if not requested otherwise (class `SubmodelAdder` of module `importtools`).
Let application models `wland_v001` and `wland_v002` use the new `prepare_submodel` decorator for submodels that comply with the `PETModel_V1` interface.

Apply the new `prepare_submodel` features to the application model `ga_garto_submodel1` and all application models of base model `lland`.

So far, the "prepare part" of the `SoilModel_V1` interface only addresses the number of soil compartments.  It seems reasonable to let the models share other information as well, but we still lack experience using `ga_garto_submodel`, so we postpone this step.

Add Mypy to the automatic test suite.

 * Add a relatively lax `mypy.ini` that does not result in errors when applying Mypy 1.0.  (We will successively increase strictness later, especially regarding the `models` package.)
 * Let the "mypy" nox session use `mypy.ini`.
 * Apply the "mypy" nox session on Travis-CI.
 * Add the `types-docutils` to `requirements.txt`.
 * Use HydPy's `typing_` module to import and reexport all used features of the standard library's `typing` module and the separately distributed `typing_extensions` module.  (Less noise in the namespaces and, hopefully, less work when switching to future Python versions.)
 * Use `Property` of module `propertytools` instead of the property builtin in some places when the setter differs from the getter (still not handled by Mypy).
 * Remove the buggy Vector and Matrix Protocols of module `typingtools` with alternatives that rely on `Sequence` and `NDArray`.  (That makes everything more consistent and prepares to include shape information via variadic generics as soon as Mypy and numpy support it.)
 * Start using `Self`.
 * Replace `objecttools.assert_never` with `typing.assert_never`.
 * Many fixes!
 * Remove outdated `type: ignore` comments.
 * Remove the substrings ".values" and ".value" before cythonizing model methods.
 * Replace `__hydpy__get_value__`, `__hydpy__set_value__`, `__hydpy__get_shape__`, `__hydpy__set_shape__` by "normal" `_get_value`, `_set_value`, `_get_shape`, _set_shape` methods.
 * Export all model constants by using literals.
Improve how (or, more precisely, when) class `ARMA` updates its instances' "AR" and "MA" coefficients.
Fix a (crash-causing) bug in method `prepare_hvector` of class `ProfileMixin` of module `lstream_model`.
Move parameter `RH1` from the `RESULTSEQUENCES` to the `DERIVEDPARAMETERS` tuple of class `Calc_EI_V1` of base model `wland`.
Prevent documenting members of `typing` and `typing_extensions` accidentally as members of `typingtools` (or other HydPy modules).

Enable the `attr-defined` checks for the `models` subpackage.

Having this check disabled proved as a significant disadvantage when refactoring or extending models.  Enabling this check required a temporary solution for the dynamically added attributes of the `Model` and `FastAccess` instances.  I decided to (temporarily) add `__getattr__` and  `__setattr__` using `Any` in both cases.  Due to this hack, Mypy cannot detect some other problems for now.  Still, I think this is okay since their amount seems negligible compared to the previously invisible problems that Mypy can detect now.

Extract the submodels `evap_m` and `evap_mlc` from `lland` and `wland` and implement the first required functionalities for exchanging land type information between main models and submodels.

`evap_m` and `evap_mlc` are the first submodels which other submodels.

The main changes:

 * Make `NameParameter`, `KeywordParameter1D`, and `KeywordParameter2D` "dynamic" so that submodels that use these classes can adopt the land cover types of their main models.
 * Define `ConstantGroups` and let `SubmodelAdder` pass them to the new general interface method `transfer_constants`.
 * Remove all "reference evapotranspiration to potential evapotranspiration" features from `lland` and `wland` and add them to `evap`.
 * Rename `Base_PETModel_V1` of `evap` to `Sub_PETModel_V1` and introduce `Main_PETModel_V1` (this should be the new convention, as it prevents name collisions and hopefully clarifies the purpose of the respective base class).
 * Extend the `PETSubmodel_V1` interface with method `prepare_zonetypes` and adjust `lland`, `wland`, and `evap` accordingly.
 * Let the "evaporation delay" of `lland` now target potential evapotranspiration instead of reference evapotranspiration (does not make a difference for the results).
 * Adjust the integration tests of `wland_v001`, `wland_v002`, and `lland_v1` by removing the now obsolete columns.
 * Add the argument `idx` to `Model.load_data` and the corresponding cythonized methods.
Increase the performance of function `hsepd` of module `statstools` a little by not applying `numpy.clip` on scalar floats.

Extend the "configuration sharing" mechanism between main models and submodels.

 * Extend the typed dictionary `ConstantGroups` so that its instances can contain all kinds of data that main models and submodels can currently share.
 * Let the `SubmodelAdder` work with the new `SharableConfigurations` specification.
 * Rename `ConstantGroups` to `SharableConfiguration`.
 * Rename the general interface method `transfer_constants` to `share_configuration` and extend its scope.
 * Improve the type hints of module `masktools` and eliminate the `_MaskDescriptor` mixin.
 * Add the class `SubmodelIndexMask` to module `masktools`.
 * Add the `_refweights` attribute to class `Variable` of module `variabletools`.
 * Let the method `modify_constants` of class `NameParameter`, `modify_entries` of class `KeywordParameter1D`, and `modify_rows` and `modify_columns` of class `KeywordParameter2D` accept `None` and do nothing if it is given  (module `parametertools`).
 * Let the method `modify_entries` of class `KeywordParameter1D` and `modify_rows` and `modify_columns` of class `KeywordParameter2D` only accept `Constants` instances for simplicity (module `parametertools`).
 * Derive most 1-dimensional parameters of HydPy-Evap from class `ZipParameter`, using the new `SubmodelIndexMask`.
 * Let all 1-dimensional sequences of HydPy-Evap use ``SubmodelIndexMask` instances.
 * Let `wland` and `lland` use the added features for sharing more configuration data with their evap submodels.
Support defining individual docstrings for all `BaseMask` instances (module `masktools`).

Simplify the "elevation adjustments` of `hland` by assuming that all given meteorological inputs fit the subbasin's average elevation.

 * Replace the control parameters `ZRelE`, `ZRelP`, and `ZRelT` with the (automatically calculated) derived parameter `Z`.
 * Remove the control parameter `TMean`. (This introduces a small difference in the calculation of `EP` for cases where `ZRelT` differs from the average basin elevation. However, this is irrelevant for typical configurations, and I think the new behaviour is more consistent.)
 * Add the control parameter `TCorr` (I needed it to keep the changes in the integration test results small. Also, as `hland` also defines `PCorr` and `ECorr`, adding `TCorr` seems like an increase in consistency. So I think we should keep it.)
 * Adjust the integration tests of all application models. (I made many intermediate checks, especially to ensure replacing the old parameters with `Z` does not change the results.)
 * Adjust the `LahnH` example project and the many doctests relying on it.

Stop deriving class `Variable` of module `variabletools` from `abc.ABC`.

This change circumvents the following problem that occurs when applying `issubclass` on `LazyInOutSequenceImport` instances:

      File "<frozen abc>", line 123, in __subclasscheck__
    TypeError: issubclass() arg 1 must be a class

Move all functionalities for calculating potential evapotranspiration from `hland` and its application models to the new submodel `evap_hbv96`.

This change requires more general framework modifications than expected due to `evap_hbv96` requiring precipitation as input data.  Therefore, we introduce the new interface `PrecipModel_V2` and its first implementation `meteo_precip_io`.  Also, this commit enables using main models that comply with the new `PrecipModel_V1` interface as "sub-submodels".

The details:

 * Let all `hland` application models use the `PETModel_V1` interface and follow the `PrecipModel_V1` interface.
 * Adjust the integration tests of all `hland` application models (all results remain unchanged in the given precision).
 * Add the `PrecipModel_V1` interface for querying precipitation from a main model used as a submodel.
 * Add the `PrecipModel_V2` interface for querying precipitation from a "real" submodel.
 * Add method `add_mainmodel_as_subsubmodel` to the `SubmodelInterface` defined in module `modeltools` and let `SubmodelAdder` call it automatically to allow submodels using their main models as sub-submodels.
 * Introdue the `...model_is_mainmodel` attributes to avoid infinite recursion when using main models as sub-submodels.
 * Add the descriptor `SubmodelIsMainmodelProperty` to module `modeltools`.
 *  add the `include_feedback` option to method `find_submodels` of class `Model` of model `modeltools` and avoid infinite recursion with the help of "...model_is_mainmodel` attributes.
 *  Let method `prepare_model` of class `IntegrationTest` of module `testtools` also update the derived parameters of the relevant submodels.
 * Update the control files of the `LahnH` example project.
 * Add the `...model_is_mainmodel` attributes on the Cython level (model `modelutils`).
 * Add the submodel `meteo_precip_io` to the `HydPy-Meteo` model family.
 * Add the submodel `evap_hbv96` to the HydPy-Evap model family.
 * Remove all functionalities for calculating potential evapotranspiration from base model `hland`.
 * Let all application models of `hland` follow the `PrecipModel_V1` interface.
 * Let application models of `lland_v1` follow the `PrecipModel_V1` interface.
 * Let application models of `wland_v001` and `wland_v002` follow the `PrecipModel_V1` interface.
 * Add the required NetCDF submodel support.
 * Adjust the XML files of the `LahnH` example project.

Introduce the temperature-related submodel interfaces `TempModel_V1` and `TempModel_V2` (module `tempinterfaces`).

The new interfaces come with the following changes in our model collection:
 * Add `meteo_temp_io` to the HydPy-Meteo model family, which follows the `TempModel_V2` interface.
 * Let all application models of `hland` and `wland` and the application model `lland_v1` follow the new `TempModel_V1` interface.
 * Let the application models `evap_fao56`, `evap_tw2002`, and `evap_hbv96` query their input temperature from submodels following the `TempModel_V1` or the `TempModel_V2` interface.
Adjust the filenames of the `LahnH` time series to use `evap_hbv96` as a submodel of `hland_v1`.
Modify the `element` property of class `Model` of module `modeltools` so that all (sub)submodels of a main model reference the same `Element` instance.

Support writing control files (including auxiliary files) that contain submodel definitions.

This commit moves the function `get_controlfileheader` and the method `save_controls` of class `Parameters` of module `parametertools` to class `Model` of module `modeltools` and modifies them as needed.

Also, it adds the `submodelname` attribute to class `SubmodelAdder` and lets `SubmodelAdder` instances register themselves to their master `Model` class under this name.  This connection is required to inspect a specific submodel's `SubmodelAdder` configuration.  (Perhaps, a more direct approach would be possible?).

Avoid requiring multiple interfaces for one submodel type in Cython.

Unfortunately, Cython extension classes do neither allow multiple inheritance nor support any other way to let one type follow multiple interfaces (at least, to my knowledge).  So, we came up with the ugly solution of introducing a single `MasterInterface` in Cython that collects all methods of the original pure-Python interfaces.  We hope there is not too much risk this hack will result in later problems because it is quite well hidden from framework users.  However, when Cython improves at this point, we should resume our old path.

This commit also adds the `SubmodelTypeIDProperty` descriptor, which works similarly to the `SubmodelIsMainmodelProperty`.  I realised that the interfaces' constant `typeid` properties were not enough to let main models identify submodels when they could follow multiple interfaces.  Maybe we should find a way to combine the submodel, the `typeid`, and the `submodel_is_mainmodel` information in one attribute later.
Fix a mix-up of the `soiltype_refindices` and the `landtype_refindices` in the call method of class `SubmodelAdder` of module `importtools`.
Use the `include_mainmodel` option of method `find_submodels` of class `Model` of module `modeltools` to refactor some methods of class `Element` of module `devicetools`.

Let us hope they will disappear with later sphinx versions.

Stop method `Calc_NetLongwaveRadiation_V1` from calculating unrealistically high net longwave radiations when the given global radiation is accidentally (much) larger than the estimated clear sky solar radiation.

We encountered some situations at dawn where the combination of small global radiation inputs and nearly zero clear sky radiation estimates could result in extreme net longwave radiation values and, subsequently, vast amounts of condensation for `evap_fao56`.  This commit should fix this problem roughly.  However, `Calc_NetLongwaveRadiation_V1`still seems very sensitive to data inconsistencies during dawn and dusk.  We should check for a need for further improvements later.

Secure method `Calc_DailyNetLongwaveRadiation_V1` of base model `evap` in the same way against too-high sunshine inputs as commit 203d3e8b00f7e5886fad48733b44298e8efd88a1 secures method `Calc_NetLongwaveRadiation_V1` against too-high global radiation inputs.

Due to relying on daily sunshine duration values, the old variant of `Calc_DailyNetLongwaveRadiation_V1` should not be as sensitive as the old variant of `Calc_NetLongwaveRadiation_V1`.  However, we apply the same trimming for safety and consistency reasons.
Fix the notation of the basic equation of method `Calc_WindSpeed2m_V1` of base model `evap`.
Add `type_ignore` to silence a false positive to method `provide_jitaccess` of class `NetCDFInterface` of module `netcdftools`.

Change how `Variable` instances react on the `len` operator and move the old functionality to the new property `numberofvalues` (module `variabletools`).

I find this change somewhat unfavourable from the typing perspective (`len` now causes a `TypeError` for some but not all variables).  However, the change seems necessary because numpy gradually makes its handling of scalar and 1-dimensional arrays with a single value stricter, which now reveals an already existing problem.  A mathematical operation (e.g. multiplication) applied on a numpy float and a 0-dimensional `Variable` instance might return a 1-dimensional, single-value array.  This only happens when the numpy flow is the first operand, which triggers numpy to analyse the `Variable` instance by calling `__len__` and `__getitem__`.  The old implementation of `__len__` causes numpy to come to false conclusions.
Use `http://127.0.0.1:8080` instead of `http://localhost:8080` in all doctests of module `servertools` to reduce testing time.

Allow adding receiver sequences to fused variables.

This commits aims to support use cases like the following: An instance of the `dam_pump` model requires the water level at two other more or less "remote" locations.  It could query them, for example, from two independent `dam_pump` instances.  Currently, the `dam_pump` model must publish its water level via a sender sequence.  However, as sender sequences are not optional, we would require two versions of `dam_pump`: one that sends its water level and one that does not.  Or alternatively, we would need to introduce water level nodes in all network files that define elements for `dam_pump` even if no other model consumes its data.   To circumvent these unfavourable solutions, we decided to make the output node mechanism applicable for such cases, as it is optional.  However, this introduces the new requirement to combine output and receiver sequences in one fused variable.

This change involves unifying the connection-building mechanisms for all relevant sequence types except output sequences.  Overall, this is good (e.g. results in more consistent and understandable error messages).  But there might be a negative impact on performance.

Add the application models `dam_pump`, `dam_sluice`, and `dam_pump_sluice` to the HydPy-Dam model family.

We implement these models for improving simulations in low-land areas, where the draining of land areas via pumps and sluices often plays a more relevant role than gravity-driven runoff.  Their most unique feature is that they release water based on the difference between an inner and an outer water level.

We will probably add some irrigation-related improvements later.
